Problem One:

Explain whether each scenario is a classification or regression problem, and indicate whether we are most interested in inference or prediction. Finally, provide n (number of observations) and p (number of predictors).

  1. We collect a set of data on the top 500 firms in the US. For each firm we record profit, number of employees, industry and the CEO salary. We are interested in understanding which factors affect CEO salary.

Comment:

This would be regression since we are trying to determine a continuous output (CEO salary). Since we are trying to understand the factors that affect the output this would be inference. n would be 500 (since 500 firms), and p would be 3 (profit, # of employees, and industry) - salary not included as predictor since that is the output variable.

  1. We are considering launching a new product and wish to know whether it will be a success or a failure. We collect data on 20 similar products that were previously launched. For each product we have recorded whether it was a success or failure, price charged for the product, marketing budget, competition price,and ten other variables.

Comment:

This would be classification since we are trying to determine success or failure - which can be thought of yes/no or 1/0 (binary). Since we are trying to understand success or failure and use that information I would say this is prediction. n = 20 (# of similar products launched), and p = 13 (price, budget, competition, +10 others).

  1. We are interested in predicting the % change in the USD/Euro exchange rate in relation to the weekly changes in the world stock markets. Hence we collect weekly data for all of 2012. For each week we record the % change in the USD/Euro, the % change in the US market, the % change in the British market, and the % change in the German market.

Comment:

This would be regression since it is a continuous value we are trying to determine. We are interested in prediction for this example since it says in the prompt ‘interested in predicting’ along with the goal being to come up with a value not the relationship it has with the given info. n = 52 (# weeks in 2012), p = 3 (% change US, % change British, % change German) - % change in USD is the output variable - not used as predictor.

Problem Two:

You will now think of some real-life applications for statistical learning.

  1. Describe three real-life applications in which classification might be useful. Describe the response, as well as the predictors. Is the goal of each application inference or prediction? Explain your answer.

Comment:

  1. Will it be hot or cold tomorrow? - Response: Hot or cold (2 options - binary). Predictors: time of year, previous day temperature, historical trends, etc. The goal is prediction of the outcome - Hot or cold for that day
  2. What affects final grades the most? - Response: A, B, C, D, F. Predictors: midterm grade, hours spent studying, hours of sleep, overall gpa, grade in pre-req courses, etc. The goal is inference since we are trying to determine the relationship between the predictors and the effect on final grades.
  3. Diabetic vs non-diabetic? - Response: Positive or negative diagnosis (binary). Predictors: weight, height, medical history, genetics, diet, etc. The goal is prediction since we are just trying to determine the outcome (diagnosis) not necessarily the relationship between the diagnosis and the predictors.
  1. Describe three real-life applications in which regression might be useful. Describe the response, as well as the predictors. Is the goal of each application inference or prediction? Explain your answer.

Comment:

  1. Sales predictions for Black Friday - continuous value. Response: estimate of sales. Predictors: historical sales data, economy, inflation rate, year-to-date sales compared to previous years, etc. The goal of this is prediction since we are trying to determine the outcome.
  2. Trying to understand what leads to more sales on Black Friday. Response: sales values correlating to different predictors. Predictors: historical sales data, economy, inflation rate, year-to-date sales compared to previous years, etc. The goal of this is inference since we are now trying to understand what causes increases/decreases in sales as opposed to predicting an actual value for the sales.
  3. predicting the ERA of a pitcher - continuous (0.00 to inf). Response: ERA estimate. Predictors: historical pitching data, opponent difficulty, left vs right handed batters faced, stadium playing in, etc. The goal of this is prediction since you are trying to determine the actual era output not the relationship underlying it.

Some other coefficients to look at are origin (1.426141 which is the largest) and cylinders (-0.493376 which is the smallest). For these it means that when only looking at their effect on mpg, each unit increase in cylinder results in a -0.493376 change in mpg and each unit of origin the mpg increases by 1.426141. I am not sure what ‘Origin’ means in this regard to comment on what it means further.
  4. R^2 value is 0.8215 which means it captures the data fairly well but could be improved.

Details about model: I tried limiting the parameters by removing the binary variables and then looking into only the ones that appeared statistically significant. However, the results were too similar between the two so I chose to continue with every initial predictor. With eventual testing, I tested using just the predictors that appeared statistically significant via the p-values and another model that used just the predictors that had high correlation. Both of these resulted in good models, but the one based on the p-values was better overall. However, despite both of these being valid models with good R^2 and p-value results, the original model created was still the best obtained. The original model had and R^2 of 0.9443 compared to model2: 0.9339 and model3: 0.8772. This shows us that model2 using the statistically significant predictors captures most of the relationships, but the other predictors do contribute overall and improve the model. If the dataset was very large, model2 might be better to use since the differences are very small between it and the full model, but it uses less predictors which would save in computation time/space.
